The paper discusses the problem of rank aggregation, which involves aggregating the preferences of multiple agents. This is a common problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG), where it is important to combine the preferences of multiple sources of information. The paper also discusses the use of dynamic programming algorithms, which are commonly used in computer science (cs.DS) to solve optimization problems. Additionally, the paper presents empirical results based on real-world and randomly generated problem instances, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the field of computational complexity (cs.CC) and social networks (cs.SI).
